  "text": "Node.js implements comprehensive command injection prevention for the child_process module through a multi-layered approach combining JavaScript argument validation and C++ native binding security checks.\n\n## JavaScript Validation Layer\n\nThe primary command injection prevention occurs in `lib/child_process.js`, which implements the public API for spawning child processes. The key validator is `validateArgumentNullCheck` (lines 963-967), which prevents null-byte injection by checking if any string argument contains the null character '\\u0000'. This function is called on:\n\n1. **File paths**: The `file` argument in `spawn()`, `execFile()`, and `spawnSync()` (line 540)\n2. **Command strings**: In `normalizeExecArgs()` for both `exec()` and `execSync()` (line 190)\n3. **Argument arrays**: In `normalizeSpawnArguments()`, the entire args array is validated via `validateArgumentsNullCheck()` (line 556)\n4. **Options parameters**: \n   - `options.argv0` (line 597)\n   - `options.shell` (line 613)\n   - `options.execPath` in `fork()` (line 142)\n   - `options.execArgv` in `fork()` (line 146)\n   - Environment variables both keys and values (lines 691-692)\n\nThe `normalizeSpawnArguments()` function (lines 538-709) is the central validation point for the `spawn()` function, which is used by all other child_process functions (`exec()`, `execFile()`, and `fork()`). It validates not only arguments but also constructs the command for shell invocation, ensuring no null bytes can escape into the shell.\n\n## Internal ChildProcess Class\n\nThe `lib/internal/child_process.js` file defines the `ChildProcess` class (lines 254-313) that extends EventEmitter. The `ChildProcess.prototype.spawn()` method (lines 354-479) receives the normalized options from JavaScript and calls `this._handle.spawn(options)`, where `_handle` is a Process object created via the native C++ binding.\n\n## C++ Native Layer\n\nThe `src/process_wrap.cc` file implements the `ProcessWrap` class, which is the C++ wrapper around libuv's process management. The `ProcessWrap::Spawn()` method (lines 153-310) receives already-validated options from JavaScript. This creates a critical security boundary - by the time C++ code receives the spawn options, all null-byte validation has already occurred in JavaScript, preventing any injection vectors at the native level.\n\nThe C++ code also includes additional Windows-specific protections, such as rejecting batch files directly (lines 203-206) to prevent potential unescaped argument vulnerabilities on Windows.\n\n## Permission System Integration\n\nThe `src/permission/child_process_permission.cc` file implements permission system integration for child process spawning. The `ProcessWrap::Spawn()` method checks permissions before allowing process creation (lines 158-159), adding an additional security layer through Node.js's permission model.\n\n## Vulnerability Prevention\n\nThis multi-layered defense prevents several command injection attack vectors:\n\n1. **Null-byte injection**: The `validateArgumentNullCheck()` function prevents null bytes that could be used to terminate string arguments early in C string-based APIs\n2. **Shell command injection**: By validating command strings in `normalizeExecArgs()` and ensuring shell arguments are properly constructed\n3. **Environment variable injection**: Both keys and values in the environment dictionary are validated to prevent injection through environment variables\n4. **Path traversal and injection in argv0**: The `options.argv0` parameter is validated to prevent process name spoofing or injection\n\nThe comprehensive test file `test/parallel/test-child-process-reject-null-bytes.js` validates that null bytes are properly rejected in all entry points (exec, execFile, spawn, fork, and their synchronous variants) and all parameter types (file, command, args, cwd, argv0, shell, environment variables, execPath, and execArgv)."
}

